# Day 46 – Task S-1: Selecting the High Baseline for OpenMRS | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## From Categorization to Controls — The Select Step Begins

The Prepare step built the foundation. The Categorize step produced the official High categorization, reviewed and approved by the AO. Today begins the Select step — where the security program takes concrete shape in the form of specific controls that will be implemented, assessed, and maintained for the life of the system.

Before going further I want to address the baseline selection directly. The original version of today's content selected the Moderate baseline. The categorization approved on Day 45 is High — and FIPS 200 is unambiguous: the control baseline must correspond to the system's security categorization. A High-impact system requires the High baseline from NIST SP 800-53B. Selecting Moderate for a High-impact system is not a conservative simplification — it is a compliance gap that would be identified immediately in any formal assessment.

Today I work through what the High baseline actually contains, why it is more demanding than Moderate in the areas that matter most for OpenMRS, and what the baseline selection means for the work ahead.

---

## What I Worked On Today

NIST SP 800-37 Task S-1 asks the organization to select the security controls for the information system based on the security categorization and to document the selected controls in the System Security Plan. The process has three components: identifying the initial control baseline from NIST SP 800-53B that corresponds to the categorization, reviewing the baseline for applicability through scoping considerations, and supplementing with additional controls where needed based on the risk assessment findings.

Today covers the first component — identifying and understanding the High baseline. Days 47 and 48 will cover tailoring (scoping and supplementing) and the HIPAA overlay mapping.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The thing that clicked most clearly today is what the difference between the Moderate and High baselines actually means in practice — not as an abstract number of controls, but as specific, meaningful security requirements.

The High baseline is not just more controls. It is more demanding requirements in the control families that matter most for a system like OpenMRS. Understanding those differences is what makes the baseline selection a substantive security decision rather than a bureaucratic category.

The most significant differences between Moderate and High for OpenMRS are in four areas: access control, audit and accountability, contingency planning, and system and communications protection. In each of those areas, the High baseline adds requirements that directly address the risk scenarios documented in Days 37 and 38.

---

## What the High Baseline Requires — Control Family by Control Family

The NIST SP 800-53B High baseline covers all twenty control families. I am going to work through the families most directly relevant to the OpenMRS risk profile in detail, and provide a summary reference for the remaining families.

---

### Access Control (AC) — High Baseline

The AC family governs who can access the system and under what conditions. The High baseline requirements go significantly beyond Moderate in areas directly relevant to the insider threat and credential compromise risks in the OpenMRS risk register.

**AC-2 Account Management:** High baseline requires automated mechanisms for account management — creating, enabling, disabling, and removing accounts — with notifications to account managers when accounts are no longer needed. For OpenMRS, this means the account deprovisioning process must be automated or semi-automated rather than purely manual. The four-hour termination response window from the risk register is supported by automation, not just policy.

**AC-2(1) Account Management — Automated System Account Management:** High adds the requirement to use automated mechanisms to support account management. This enhancement is not in the Moderate baseline — it is specific to High-impact systems. For OpenMRS, this means integrating account management with the enterprise identity provider discussed on Day 40 rather than managing accounts manually in the OpenMRS application.

**AC-3(7) Access Enforcement — Role-Based Access Control:** High baseline explicitly requires role-based access control as an enhancement to the base access enforcement requirement. For OpenMRS, every user must have a role that defines their access scope — clinical roles can access patient records within their care relationship; administrative roles are scoped to registration and scheduling functions; IT roles have no clinical record access.

**AC-6 Least Privilege:** High baseline adds AC-6(1) (authorize access to security functions for security personnel only), AC-6(2) (require non-privileged accounts for non-security functions — even administrators should use standard user accounts for routine clinical tasks), AC-6(5) (restrict privileged access to the minimum necessary), and AC-6(9) (log use of privileged functions). The combination of these enhancements means that privilege management for OpenMRS needs to be explicitly documented, reviewed, and monitored — not just applied at setup and forgotten.

**AC-17 Remote Access:** High baseline adds requirements for automated monitoring of remote access sessions. For OpenMRS, remote clinical access via VPN requires session monitoring and defined conditions under which remote sessions are terminated. Staff accessing patient records from home or on mobile devices need to understand that those sessions are subject to the same monitoring as in-clinic sessions.

**AC-17(1) Remote Access — Automated Monitoring and Control:** This High enhancement requires automated monitoring of remote access — a capability that connects directly to the GuardDuty and CloudWatch monitoring discussed in Day 28. Unusual remote access patterns — unexpected geographic origins, access at unusual hours, high-volume record access — should generate alerts.

*Connection to risk register:* AC enhancements directly address RS-004 (insider PHI misuse) and RS-005 (phishing and credential compromise).

---

### Audit and Accountability (AU) — High Baseline

The AU family governs the generation, protection, and review of audit records. For a HIPAA-covered system, the AU family is where the technical safeguard audit control requirement lives — and the High baseline is significantly more demanding than Moderate.

**AU-2 Event Logging:** High baseline requires logging of a more comprehensive set of events than Moderate. For OpenMRS, the required events include: successful and unsuccessful login attempts, access to patient records (read and write), changes to user accounts and permissions, use of administrative functions, changes to audit logging configuration (attempts to disable or modify logging are high-priority events), and security-relevant system events.

**AU-3 Content of Audit Records:** High baseline requires that audit records contain sufficient information to establish what event occurred, when it occurred, where it occurred, the source of the event, the outcome of the event, and the identity of individuals or subjects associated with the event. For OpenMRS application audit logs, this means: user identifier, timestamp with timezone, patient record identifier accessed, action type (view/create/modify/delete), outcome (success/failure), and source IP address.

**AU-6 Audit Record Review, Analysis, and Reporting:** High baseline requires automated tools to integrate and analyze audit records — not just manual periodic review. This pushes the monitoring program from the weekly manual log review in the Day 30 monitoring strategy toward tool-supported anomaly detection. AWS Security Hub and CloudWatch Logs Insights provide some of this capability; the application-level audit logs need a review process that can surface anomalous patterns.

**AU-6(1) Audit Record Review — Automated Process Integration:** This High enhancement requires integrating the audit review process with automated analysis — specifically to support near-real-time detection of suspicious activity. For insider threat detection (RS-004), this means the audit log review cannot wait for the weekly manual review cycle; high-priority events should generate real-time alerts.

**AU-9 Protection of Audit Information:** High baseline adds requirements to protect audit information from unauthorized access, modification, and deletion — and to alert on any attempts to modify or delete audit records. For OpenMRS, this means CloudWatch Log Groups must have IAM policies that prevent deletion, and any API call that attempts to delete or modify audit logs must generate a high-priority alert via CloudTrail.

**AU-9(3) Protection of Audit Information — Cryptographic Protection:** High enhancement requires cryptographic mechanisms to protect audit record integrity. CloudTrail log file validation — which uses SHA-256 hashing to verify that log files have not been modified after delivery — implements this requirement for AWS API audit logs.

**AU-12 Audit Record Generation:** High baseline requires that the information system generate audit records for the events defined in AU-2 from all system components. This means the OpenMRS application, the EC2 OS, and the AWS services all need to generate consistent audit records — not just some components.

*Connection to risk register:* AU enhancements directly address RS-004 (insider PHI misuse) by ensuring comprehensive, tamper-evident audit logging with automated anomaly detection.

