### Identification and Authentication (IA) — High Baseline

The IA family governs how users prove their identity before accessing the system. The High baseline MFA requirements are one of the clearest differentiators from Moderate and one of the most important controls for the OpenMRS risk profile.

**IA-2 Identification and Authentication — Organizational Users:** High baseline requires MFA for all access — not just remote access, not just privileged access, but all access to the system. For OpenMRS, this means every clinical and administrative user must authenticate with a second factor for every login session, including in-clinic workstation access.

**IA-2(1) MFA for Privileged Access:** High baseline explicitly requires MFA for privileged accounts (IT administrators, ISSO) — this requirement exists in both Moderate and High baselines.

**IA-2(2) MFA for Non-Privileged Access:** This is the High-baseline enhancement that is not in the Moderate baseline. It requires MFA for all non-privileged users — clinical staff, administrative staff, everyone. For OpenMRS, this is the control that most directly addresses RS-001 (ransomware via credential compromise) and RS-005 (phishing and credential compromise). A phished password without the second factor cannot access the system.

**IA-5 Authenticator Management:** High baseline adds requirements for authenticator protection — minimum password length and complexity, password change on first use, prohibition on reuse of recent passwords, and requirements for protecting authenticators against disclosure. The High enhancement IA-5(1) adds automated enforcement of these password composition and lifetime rules.

**IA-8 Identification and Authentication — Non-Organizational Users:** High baseline requires identification and authentication for the laboratory API integration and any other non-human connections to OpenMRS. Service account credentials for API integrations must be managed with the same rigor as human user credentials — separate credentials for each integration, minimum necessary permissions, rotation on defined schedule.

*Connection to risk register:* IA enhancements directly address RS-001 and RS-005 as the primary technical control against credential-based attacks.

