## High vs. Moderate — The Controls That Matter Most for OpenMRS

| Control | Moderate Baseline | High Baseline | Risk Register Connection |
|---|---|---|---|
| IA-2(2) MFA for non-privileged users | Not required | Required | RS-001, RS-005 |
| AC-2(1) Automated account management | Not required | Required | RS-004 |
| AU-6(1) Automated audit analysis | Not required | Required | RS-004 |
| AU-9(3) Cryptographic audit protection | Not required | Required | RS-004 |
| CP-6 Alternate storage site | Not required | Required | RS-006 |
| CP-7(1) Alternate processing site separation | Not required | Required | RS-006 |
| SC-7(5) Deny-by-default boundary protection | Not required | Required | RS-001, RS-002 |
| IR-4(1) Automated incident handling | Not required | Required | All RS |

These eight controls — all required at High but not at Moderate — represent the most significant security investments that the High categorization drives. Each maps directly to one or more risk scenarios in the Day 38 risk register. This is why the categorization decision matters: Moderate would not require these controls, and the risk register shows these controls are specifically needed for the threat environment OpenMRS faces.

