## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While reviewing the High baseline control families today I came back to the **2020 SolarWinds supply chain attack** — which I covered on Day 6 — to look at it through the specific lens of which High baseline controls would have aided detection.

The SolarWinds attack was characterized by extraordinary stealth — attackers operated within compromised environments for months without detection. Post-incident analysis identified several monitoring gaps that enabled the long dwell time: audit logging that was not comprehensive enough to capture the attackers' lateral movement; alert thresholds set too broadly to surface the specific anomalies the attackers generated; and incident response processes that were not sufficiently automated to escalate the signals that did exist.

The High baseline requirements for AU-6(1) (automated audit analysis), IR-4(1) (automated incident handling), and AC-6(9) (logging of privileged function use) are all directly relevant to the SolarWinds detection failure. Organizations with those controls implemented at the High baseline level would have had better automated visibility into the anomalous activity — though the sophistication of the SolarWinds attack means that even robust controls might not have caught it immediately.

The broader lesson for OpenMRS is that the High baseline's emphasis on automation — automated account management, automated audit analysis, automated incident handling — reflects a recognition that manual processes cannot maintain adequate security visibility in complex environments. The High baseline is designed for systems where the consequences of a missed detection are severe — exactly the patient safety and regulatory stakes of an EHR breach.

